## Overview

The Python implementation of OnTrack (`ontrack/`) is the original version, featuring:

- **Desktop GUI** built with CustomTkinter — runs on Windows, Linux, and macOS
- **Android app** built with Kivy — deployable via buildozer as an APK
- **Google OR-Tools** integration for production-grade TSP/VRP solving
- **PyO3/maturin** build system for optional Rust-accelerated components

## Project Structure

```
ontrack/
├── main.py                 # Entry point — detects desktop vs Android
├── core/                   # Business logic (platform-independent)
│   ├── parser.py           # CSV/Excel/text → address list
│   ├── geocoder.py         # Address → lat/lng coordinates
│   ├── matrix.py           # Distance/duration matrix
│   ├── solver.py           # TSP optimizer (OR-Tools + NN fallback)
│   └── exporter.py         # CSV export, Maps/FieldMaps URLs
├── gui/                    # Desktop GUI (CustomTkinter)
│   ├── app.py              # Main application window
│   ├── components/         # Reusable widgets
│   └── views/              # Screen views (home, results, settings)
├── mobile/                 # Android GUI (Kivy)
│   ├── app.py              # Kivy application
│   └── screens/            # Mobile screens
├── tests/                  # pytest test suite
├── assets/                 # Images, themes
├── pyproject.toml          # Build config (maturin)
├── requirements.txt        # Desktop dependencies
├── requirements-android.txt # Android dependencies
├── ontrack.spec            # PyInstaller config
└── buildozer.spec          # Android build config
```

## Key Dependencies

| Package | Purpose |
|---------|---------|
| pandas | DataFrame operations for address data |
| openpyxl | Excel file reading |
| geopy | Geocoding abstraction layer |
| requests | HTTP client for APIs |
| ortools | Google OR-Tools TSP/VRP solver |
| python-dotenv | .env file loading |
| routingpy | Routing engine abstraction |
| customtkinter | Modern Tkinter-based GUI |
| Pillow | Image processing |
| folium | Map rendering |

## Platform Detection

`main.py` auto-detects the runtime environment:

```python
try:
    import android
    _PLATFORM = "android"
except ImportError:
    _PLATFORM = "desktop"
```

On Android (built via buildozer/python-for-android), the `android` module is available. On desktop, it falls back to the CustomTkinter GUI. The `--mobile` flag can force mobile mode for testing.

